<TEXT>
a british citizen who was captured in rome last 
may after five years as a fugitive was fined 25000 tuesday after 
pleading guilty to violating export controls by selling computer 
equipment to eastern bloc countries 
in an arrangement with the us justice department brian moller 
butcher of london pleaded guilty to five counts of violating the 
commodities control act by funneling computer and laboratory 
equipment through britain to poland bulgaria and romania fourteen 
other counts were dropped 
in addition to the fines butcher was sentenced to time already 
served he had been held since his arrest 
the justice department contended the items were computer 
processors that had military applications but butcher said the 
equipment was lowtech hewlettpackard test lab equipment that 
could have been purchased in a number of countries but was cheaper 
in the united states 
theyre of dual use they had commercial and military uses 
assistant us attorney kevin f driscoll said in recommending 
butcher be sentenced to two years in prison and fined 150000 
but us district judge rya zobel said she did not see the need 
for so severe a sentence i may be obtuse but i dont see it 
she said 
there was no breach of security to the nato countries or the 
united states defense attorney paul f markham said the only 
way these could have hurt someone is if they had dropped out of an 
airplane and hit them on the head 
butcher and paul carlson a us citizen were indicted in 1981 
for the scheme carlson pleaded guilty and was fined 5000 when 
the case came to trial in 1983 butcher 55 said after appearing 
in court tuesday that he had fled the united states because of the 
nations political climate 
things got rather hot politically in the early days of 
president ronald reagan he said i think things have cooled 
off now and reason has returned 
sources told the associated press an associate of butchers 
indicted on similar charges in phoenix became a government 
informant and lured butcher to his arrest in rome under the pretext 
of another illegal export scheme 
</TEXT>
