<TEXT>
propalestinian and israeli forces are 
clashing in this highbrow academic enclave over ballot questions 
addressing the turbulent politics of the occupied west bank 
the cambridge referendum calls for support in demanding that 
israel end its violations of palestinian human rights and its 
occupation of the west bank and gaza the referendum also calls 
for cutting off us taxpayers money for israels occupation of 
the west bank and gaza and for creating an independent 
palestinian state in the west bank and gaza with peace for all 
states in the region including israel 
cambridge home to harvard and the massachusetts institute of 
technology is a frequent forum for vigorous political debate the 
city with a population of 90000 people also has many 
workingclass neighborhoods and members of jewish organizations 
said they expected the majority of voters would not support the 
referendum 
similar questions are on ballots in san francisco and berkeley 
calif 
only cambridge and berkeley would have the chutzpah to think 
that they can determine national and international policy by a 
local ballot on as complicated an issue said harvard law school 
professor alan dershowitz 
clearly it is simply designed as a strident antiisrael 
unbalanced message he said 
but supporters say they are providing an outlet for what they 
perceive as a growing disenchantment with us policy in the middle 
east stoked by the recent uprisings on the west bank 
we feel the status quo simply is intolerable said matthew 
gordon spokesman for the coalition for palestinian rights which 
gathered signatures to put the questions on the ballot 
gordon said his group opposes israeli policies not israel and 
realizes you cant tackle the entire problem in just one 
referendum 
we dont hope ourselves to change it us policy but we 
feel that were part of a movement he said 
diane steinman new england director of the american jewish 
committee said the national office of the organization is opposing 
the referendum in cambridge and also a separate ballot question in 
newton just across the charles river 
the newton question asks voters to support creation of a 
separate palestinian state in the occupied territories and 
security for israel and the palestinian state 
we believe in general that ballot referenda like these are not 
an effective mechanism for addressing the complexity of the issues 
in the middle east steinman said 
in newton which has a substantial jewishamerican population 
among its 82000 residents the national committee for arab and 
israeli peace is preparing for a different campaign andrea barron 
chairwoman of the organization said the commitee is not related to 
the cambridge group 
we deliberately chose newton because an increasing number of 
jewishamericans are willing to support a palestinian state said 
barron noting that she is jewish 
opponents and proponents said they intend to wage a fullfledged 
campaign on the referendums 
i think its a serious issue dershowitz said if only a 
few people show up and vote on this ballot you can always get a 
yes pushed through 
gordon said the coalition is distributing fliers mailing out 
letters and has so far raised at least 2000 
the jewish community relations council which includes 34 
organizations plans to stay within a modest budget in its 
opposition campaign details of which are still being discussed 
said group president joel reck 
we intend to coordinate efforts to defeat these referenda 
which we consider inimicable to the peace process he said 
no one least of all israel likes the present situation of 
occupied territories reck said the question is how do we 
support israel and be supportive of israel and having referenda on 
what israel ought to do is an absurd and inappropriate way to 
address what are the very serious problems in the middle east 
</TEXT>
