<TEXT>
apartment construction in august sunk to the 
lowest level in more than six years outweighing a small gain in 
singlefamily home building the government said wednesday 
the commerce department said housing construction fell 33 
percent last month to an annual level of 144 million units a 169 
percent plunge in the volatile apartment category to 350000 units 
more than offset a 21 percent gain in singlefamily homes to 109 
million units 
the singlefamily home category has fluctuated in a fairly 
narrow range this year at an annual rate of around 11 million 
units however the apartment sector has approached a rate of 
500000 units in some months and now rests at its lowest point 
since june 1982 when the last recession was ending 
the singlefamily level is pretty good its been an 
incredibly stable element of the market but the multiunit number 
is staggering said david seiders chief economist of the 
national association of home builders 
analysts have been expecting housing activity to taper off 
because the federal reserve board has been pushing up interest 
rates since late march in an effort to curb inflation 
but seiders said home buyers appear to be turning to adjustable 
rate mortgages which cost less than fixedrate mortgages but whose 
rates can change 
also fixedrate mortgages have not risen as fast as many 
economists were expecting according to the federal home loan 
mortgage corp fixedrate mortgages not including addon fees 
known as points hit a high of 1071 percent in midaugust but have 
since eased dropping to 104 percent last week 
the overall decline in august housing starts followed gains of 
14 percent in july and 52 percent in june 
for the first eight months of 1988 housing starts have been 
running 99 percent below the level of activity during the same 
period in 1987 singlefamily construction is lagging by 67 
percent while apartment construction trails by 176 percent 
mark obrinsky an economist with the us league of savings 
institutions said apartment construction was dealt a heavy blow 
when the tax law that took effect in january 1987 reduced the 
profitability of real estate investments also vacancy rates are 
high 
the vacancy rate for rental housing was 77 percent in the 
apriljune period this year compared with rates between 5 percent 
and 6 percent through the 1960s and 1970s he said 
building permits a good barometer of future housing activity 
were up 19 percent last month to 145 million units a year after 
falling 49 percent in july 
by region housing starts fell 207 percent in the northeast to 
207000 units and 172 percent in the midwest to 240000 
starts were up 143 percent in the west to 424000 units and up 
04 percent in the south to 565000 
the northeast is taking a beating now said michael 
sumichrast a private housing economist in washington the new 
york sales market is practically dead its still suffering from 
the financial market collapse and layoffs in the securities 
industry 
