when oil prices fell in 1986 support surged 
for carl i hagens small but boistrous antitax party 
the progress party once shunned as a rightwing fringe group 
has been surging ever since 
recent polls indicate the party has the support of 22 percent of 
norways voters in a political arena traditionally dominated by the 
labor party and the conservatives 
the storting parliament where the progress party has only two 
of the 157 seats appears headed for a political earthquake in 
next years elections the weekly newspaper nytt fra norge said 
recently 
antitax forces have also gained ground in denmark another 
scandinavian welfare state norway however had grown rich from 
its north sea oilfields and the 1986 price collapse hit norwegians 
particularly hard 
the standard of living has dropped in norway for the first time 
since world war ii triggering a wave of discontent and criticism 
of the established parties 
we have a whole load of solutions to the problems hagen 
tells norwegians 
hagen 44 wants to lower taxes restrict immigration cut down 
the public sector and let private companies handle traditional 
welfare state tasks such as hospital care child care and care for 
the elderly 
in a country where big welfare benefits financed through taxes 
were taken for granted even by conservatives hagens policies were 
considered extreme 
however conservative party policies recently outlined 
borrowed some of hagens ideas an apparent attempt to ride the 
trend in advance of the elections set for sept 11 1989 
hagen is a powerful speaker who often shouts down opponents in 
the storting a chamber more accustomed to hushed and polite tones 
sitting amid piles of newspaper clippings at his small office in 
the storting building hagen told a visitor that the state handles 
defense schools hospitals in a miserably poor way 
he claimed the scandinavian welfare state does not function well 
because he said it is modeled after east bloc socialism and 
acts as a guardian interfering in all things between heaven and 
earth 
a strong advocate of a freemarket economy hagen maintains the 
governments functions should be restricted to basics such as 
defense and law and order 
