<TEXT>
the sun comes up a 
faraway fireball heralding another day of waning summer in 
yellowstone national park 
after three nervewracking months and a blessed few inches of 
early snow the walls of flame are gone the 60 mph winds that 
danced embers from treetop to treetop have died away the small 
tourist towns that hug the boundaries of the worlds first national 
park are no longer threatened with annihilation 
on the horizon is only a hint of smoke and haze 
but yellowstone is a casualty of what historians describe as its 
worst summer of drought and flames in 300 years famous around the 
world as a pristine symbol of wilderness this vast park is now a 
mosaic of green and black living forests and dead trees 
nearly half of yellowstones 22 million acres have been touched 
by fires with names like hellroaring and storm north fork and 
clover mist millions of black matchsticks are all that remain of 
oncethriving lodgepoles and blue spruce aspens and firs 
because the flames were fickle there are also huge patches of 
sweetsmelling pines growing next to miles of charred forest there 
are fragrant meadows hard by singed marsh delicate ferns turning 
gold with the equinox still grow next to creekbeds seared of every 
blade of grass 
yellowstone national park is not a total wasteland of scorched 
earth and moonscape but it is not the place it used to be 
already charges of mismanagement and bad policy are being 
leveled against park rangers congressional hearings and internal 
reviews promise to drag on from autumn into winter and beyond 
there are fears about the future of yellowstones fisheries and 
wildlife when ash and silt flow into streams and lakes next spring 
more than 8000 firefighters from the national park service 
forest service the army and even the marine corps descended on 
yellowstone to do battle taking on one of natures most awesome 
forces with picks and shovels hoses and hand tools 
daily they still crisscross the park in camouflagepainted 
armored vehicles and chartreuse pumper trucks bearing license 
plates from california to florida they overflow campgrounds with 
their tents and catering crews and line up at pay phones to call 
faraway loved ones who demand to know when theyre coming home 
but beyond the hustle of command posts and bivouacs the birds 
are singing old faithful still is trumpeter swans swimming in 
pairs still grace the madison river as it meanders through its own 
plateau the fountain paint pots still gurgle and steam and the 
mountains cast the same shadows hunters saw as far back as 5000 
years ago 
the park is just a howling wilderness of 3000 square miles 
full of all imaginable freaks of a fiery nature wrote rudyard 
kipling of yellowstone in 1889 
and so it is today 
those who come to yellowstone after the fires will still see the 
same breathtaking vista from artist point that inspired painters 
thomas moran and albert bierstadt in the 1800s 
the 700foot sheer drop and two roaring waterfalls of the grand 
canyon of the yellowstone are the same as when the parks first 
superintendent nathaniel p langford was prompted to write i 
realized my own littleness my helplessness my dread exposure to 
destruction my inability to cope with or even comprehend the 
mighty architecture of nature 
along virginia cascade drive are many unspoiled spots where 
falling pine needles have created a soft carpet of ground cover 
but farther down the slope lies graphic evidence of the ominous 
spiral of fire that swept through that place with particular fury 
right above the falls there are still little puffs of smoke and 
an occasional lick of distant flames still waiting for mopup 
crews in one turnout five tidy picnic tables stand ready for the 
next batch of campers 
in the pastoral hayden valley herds of bison graze in the 
untouched meadows a ragged chevron of geese fly overhead and the 
yellowstone river its flow diminished by drought braids its way 
through the vast open bowl bull elk are everywhere 
just as president theodore roosevelt wrote during his visit in 
1903 we saw an occasional pine squirrel snowshoe rabbit or 
marten and in the open meadows around the hot waters there were 
canada geese and ducks of several species and now and then a 
coyote 
farther south around yellowstone lake some hills on the 
horizon are charred some are not but the fabled evening stillness 
of the lake remains its surface sometimes a mirror of its 
surroundings 
the geysers erupt as they did for naturalist john muir in 1885 
the wildest geysers in the world in bright triumphant bands 
are dancing and singing in it amid thousands of boiling springs 
mud volcanoes mush and broth caldrons whose contents are of every 
color and consistency splash and heave and roar in bewildering 
abundance 
as has been the case in recent years most of yellowstones 
bears are elusive but many firefighters have seen them park 
biologists are confident the bears are still in the back country 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
tad bartimus is the ap mountain states regional 
reporter based in denver 
