<TEXT>
the financial health of farm families has been 
aided dramatically in recent years by federal subsidies but 
agriculture department economists say a good job in town is the 
real meal ticket for a growing number of those who live on the land 
all told the jobs and government payments helped push farm 
household earnings ahead of the us average in 1985 and again in 
1986 the first time that has happened since the 1970s 
the mainstay for many families has been offfarm income the job 
in town a regular paycheck that is isolated from drought and the 
whipsawing of commodity prices 
although many observers and analysts previously considered 
offfarm employment as a transitional step to fulltime farming 
operation offfarm employment is becoming more common as farm 
operators and members of their households choose to pursue dual 
careers says donn reimund of the departments economic research 
service 
the agency noted in a report last winter that offfarm incomes 
were of growing importance to farm families and that the income gap 
between farm and nonfarm narrowed again in the mid1980s after 
widening since 1978 
in the latest installment reported in a forthcoming issue of 
farmline magazine reimund and his colleagues noted that the 
incomes of farm households trailed the us average for six 
straight years before moving ahead in 1985 to an average of 29436 
against the national average for all households of 29066 a 1 
percent lead 
the gap widened in 1986 to 11 percent as the farm average rose 
to 34246 per household compared with 30759 for the us 
average both were record levels 
department analysts attributed the rise in 1985 and 1986 to 
lower production costs and higher direct government payments to 
farmers although increased incomes from offfarm jobs were also 
factors 
federal payments to farmers were 8 billion in 1985 and rose to 
12 billion in 1986 comparatively in 1981 those were only 19 
billion 
but comparisons of average incomes do not explain income 
distribution and can mask differences at the very high and low 
levels that is true of urban as well as farm families but reimund 
said a higher percentage of farm operator households are below 
the official povery level than are other households 
only about 16 percent of the nations farm families reported 
receiving no offfarm income in 1986 based on usdas annual farm 
costs and returns survey 
mary ahearn another agency analyst said that about half of the 
households of farm operators in 1986 depended on offfarm sources 
for twothirds or more of their total cash income 
these households were generally involved in small farming 
operations with sales of less than 40000 a year she said on 
the average they reported a loss of 2950 on farm operations in 
1986 but earned 40904 off the farm resulting in a net cash 
income of 37954 
only 20 percent of the households in this group participated in 
federal direct payment programs and they received an average of 
6380 each their small size precluded larger payments because 
federal subsidies are related to production 
until the 1970s the nations farm operator households lagged 
behind the us average in household incomes the report said 
today their incomes remain much more volatile than the steadily 
rising us average but no longer are they always in the bottom 
position 
farm household income exceeded the us average in eight of the 
17 years 1970 through 1986 only two of those years 1985 and 
1986 were in the 80s 
reimund said the first time was in 1972 as farm export markets 
began to grow rapidly in 1973 farm income shot up to an average 
of 17854 per household 47 percent more than the us average of 
12157 a difference that has not been matched since 
has the trend continued in 1987 and 1988 reimund said he had to 
hedge a bit particularly for this years income comparisons 
last year was pretty good he said but 1988 its a tough 
one with the drought and all i guess well just have to wait and 
see 
