<TEXT>
as more americans find themselves priced 
out of the housing market doityourself home building could get a 
taste of the good old days when thousands cut costs by raising 
their own roofs 
one company in the business miles homes believes the concept 
of sweat equity still has some attraction particularly among 
consumers with annual incomes of less than 60000 
the companys biggest years were in the late 1970s when it sold 
doityourself packages to as many as 2200 people a year many of 
whom lived in thenbooming texas 
having taken some hard licks during the recession miles is now 
happy to sell 800 homes a year but the company is optimistic about 
the future 
this is not our best year but we expect 1989 to improve 
said richard cornwall president and chief operating officer of 
miles homes 
the real heyday for doityourself home construction in this 
country was from 1900 to 1940 when two of the biggest kithome 
manufacturers were sears roebuck amp co and montgomery ward 
according to research published earlier this year by tab books inc 
of blue ridge summit pa 
sears alone sold more than 100000 kit homes from 1900 until the 
start of world war ii when all domestic construction came to a 
virtual standstill according to tab 
it wasnt until the late 1960s that a resurgence in the 
doityourself attitude and an upswing in construction costs caused 
kit homes to become popular again tab says 
since that time the industry has grown to the point where about 
20 percent of the new singlefamily homes built annually in the 
united states have some degree of owner involvement according to 
the national association of home builders 
the build your own home directory says about 138000 americans 
built their own houses last year 
currently there are more than 2000 kithouse manufacturers and 
dealers nationwide according to the tab research 
although cornwall admits miles share of the market is small he 
said miles is one of the few companies in the country offering a 
complete package for the doityourselfer land evaluations 
blueprints materials construction loan money and mortgage 
financing 
under new owner peter degeorge who paid meriden connbased 
insilco corp about 100 million for the company in april miles 
has pulled in its territorial reins so that its principal markets 
are in the midwest and along the eastern seaboard 
cornwall said miles makes much of its money off the package of 
precut materials used in the construction process but the 
companys financing arm also profits when customers make good on 
the threeyear construction loans that are at the heart of the 
sales pitch 
dave dunnigan publicity director for miles said 65 percent of 
the customers are firsttime homebuyers many of them with annual 
incomes of 25000 to 60000 a year who often do not have enough 
savings to make a big down payment 
land costs not included miles will finance the purchase price 
of its homes which range from 25000 to 65000 for up to 36 
months around market rates no down payment on materials is 
required but an appraisal fee of 250 is required upon credit 
approval payments on the threeyear loan cover interest only and 
at the end of the three years the construction loan balance is due 
in full and usually is paid through the use of a mortgage which 
can be obtained from miles 
weve frontended so much money out of our pocket the 
customers are usually in a good position said scott gerber 
marketing manager but most people will not come out ahead unless 
they are involved in building it 
ideally if the customer does enough of the construction and the 
home is built in a location that has value the result will be a 
structure that is worth more than it cost to build it 
but as gerber said we have people whose expectations arent 
met 
indeed in april 1978 the federal trade commission ordered miles 
to stop making false misleading and deceptive claims related 
to the construction process for instance the company used to 
advertise that the only skill required for assembly was the 
ability to drive a nail or use a hammer 
dunnigan said the company has long since made the corrections 
and no other action has been taken by the ftc 
now when customers do not come out ahead it is usually because 
they added a luxury item like a whirlpool bath that was not called 
for in the blueprints 
only a handful of people have walked away from their houses as 
they were under construction gerber said those who have 
frustrations in the process can turn to company experts for advice 
the sweat by the way still produces some equity the council 
of american building officials says consumers can cut home 
construction expenses by 25 percent to 50 percent depending on how 
much labor they do themselves 
</TEXT>
