<TEXT>
on the eve of major talks on the worlds economic 
problems former west german chancellor willy brandt made a strong 
plea wednesday to reduce the debt of third world countries due to 
reach 12 trillion by the end of the year 
what sense does it make that for years now there has been 
more money flowing from the south to the north as interest 
payments than new money flowing out of the north to the south 
he asked 
he called it a reverse blood transfusion from patient to 
doctor the flow has been estimated at 30 billion annually in 
recent years 
traditionally poor developing countries like the united 
states 150 years ago have received more money in new loans than 
they were paying as interest in this century the rich countries 
are in the northern hemisphere the poor ones largely in the south 
the world bank and its sister organization the international 
monetary fund are holding their joint annual meetings this year in 
berlin though formal sessions start on thursday delegates have 
been arriving all week and informal contacts are taking place 
brandt said not much can be expected from the current meetings 
because of the presidential campaign in the united states 
given the situation i think the europeans would be well 
advised to take the initiative themselves he said 
michel camdessus the frenchman who is the funds managing 
director saw separate problems for rich and poor countries 
we still have serious problems to surmount especially the 
large payments imbalances among the biggest trading nations and 
the debt burdens of so many low and middleincome developing 
countries which are struggling to restore adequate levels of 
growth he said 
brandt emphasized what he saw as the responsibility of rich 
countries toward poorer ones he endorsed the criticism that the 
fund sets austere conditions for its loans that cause hardship in 
poor countries 
both brandt and camdessus spoke at a public meeting sponsored by 
a foundation called development and peace of which brandt is 
chairman at the age of 74 brandt also heads the socialist 
international a grouping of socialist and social democratic 
parties from many countries 
</TEXT>
