<TEXT>
brazil will sign an unprecedented 82 billion 
financial package with its international commercial bank creditors 
it was announced wednesday 
the deal to be signed thursday was billed by citicorp as a 
possible landmark in the third world debt crisis a preliminary 
accord was reached in july 
brazil is the biggest third world debtor with a foreign debt of 
more than 120 billion about one tenth of all third world 
external debt which is estimated at 12 trillion 
the mediumterm package is the largest ever assembled on the 
international markets said william r rhodes vice president of 
citicorp 
rhodes chairman of the 16bank committee that negotiates with 
brazil in the name of creditor banks worldwide added wednesday 
that this is the first package since the debt crisis began in 
august 1982 to combine new money with substantial debt reduction 
in that respect rhodes said the brazil package may point 
the way to the future in the management of the debt crisis 
brazilian finance minister mailson da nobrega was quoted by 
citicorp as saying that before withdrawing the first installment 
under the new money agreements possibly next month brazil will 
be current on all interest payments to its commercial bank 
creditors 
brazil suspended interest payments on its foreign bank debt for 
about a year starting in february 1987 and has beem making partial 
payments this year 
thursdays package includes 52 billion in new money to help 
brazil cover its external financing needs for 1987 1988 and the 
first half of 1989 citicorp said said this includes 36 billion 
in cofinancing and parallel financing with the world bank 1 
billion in newmoney bonds and a 600 million mediumterm trade 
facility 
the package also includes a multiyear restructuring agreement 
covering about 62 billion of brazils approximately 67 billion of 
medium and longterm debt to foreign commercial banks 
it further includes 15 billion in trade and interbank 
facilities through which international commercial banks will 
continue to extend shortterm trade and interbank lines of credit 
brazil will pay the london interbank offered rate libor plus 
1316 percent on the newmoney credits the bonds and the 
restructured debt the libor rate fluctuates daily and currently 
stands at around 85 percent 
the 62 billion of restructured debt includes private and public 
sector loans maturing from jan 1 1987 to dec 31 1993 it will be 
rescheduled over 20 years with the final maturity in 2007 
principal payments on the restructured debt will begin in 1995 
citicorp said 
the restructured debt and some of the newmoney facilities are 
eligible for conversion to investments under a brazilian 
debtforequity program creditors could thus become investors in 
brazil and their converted loans on being transformed into 
investments would reduce brazils foreign debt load 
separately wednesday in brasilia president jose sarney 
officially announced brazil had ended its foreign debt moratorium 
</TEXT>
