<TEXT>
a herd of 500 pregnant holstein cows will 
begin an 11day cruise to the canary islands next week arriving in 
plenty of time to get used to their new homes before giving birth 
an official said wednesday 
these cattle are going to have better living conditions there 
than here said william c nichol executive secretary of the 
pennsylvania holstein association there the temperatures range 
from 70 to 80 degrees yearround here they go down into the teens 
during the winter theyll be very comfortable 
a group of about 30 dairy farmers from the canary islands bought 
the heifers with the help of the us department of agricultures 
program for subsiding us farm exports dairy officials said 
the farmers paid about 1000 apiece and the us government 
kicked in a roughly equal amount officials said 
residents of the islands which form a province of spain have 
relied primarily on milk imported from europe casey said the herd 
will help the islands develop an autonomous dairy system he said 
we are very pleased with our selection said felix 
rodriguez of tenerife canary islands the 60 cows he bought from 
the lot will augment the 150 cows on his farm run before him by 
his father for 50 years they are fine animals for our farms 
the heifers will be transported to the port of wilmington where 
they will begin their 11day voyage on sept 26 aboard the athene 
a ship with three wellventilated decks nichol said 
this shipment is the third of four scheduled to go to the 
islands he said the last 900 are scheduled for shipment later 
this year and will complete the contract for 2700 holsteins 
nichol said 
the pennsylvania holstein association in cooperation with the 
holstein freisian services of vermont arranged for the export of 
the cows which come from nine states 
each heifer is expected to have about five calves during her 
lifetime nichol said after giving birth this fall they will be 
artificially inseminated to bear the next generation of holsteins 
he said 
the shipment represents the type of trade that will help 
pennsylvania set new food and agricultural export records said 
gov robert p casey after touring the stockyard 
</TEXT>
